The OSA miRs Database

1 Scientific Context

1.1 Introduction

The OSA miR database, a manually curated database, compiles experiment-supported evidence for differentially expressed microRNAs (miRNAs) in Obstructive Sleep Apnea (OSA). OSA is a sleep-related breathing disorder characterized by recurrent obstructions in the upper airways while breathing efforts persist. Each obstruction episode temporarily blocks (apneas) or reduces (hypopneas) airflow, resulting in surges in sympathetic activity and frequent arousals or microarousals during sleep. Despite being one of the most prevalent sleep disorders worldwide, the diagnosis and treatment is still difficult. Currently, the diagnosis involves a sleep study (type I to type III) that is expensive, labor-intensive, and time-consuming. Continuous Positive Airway Pressure (CPAP) is currently the first-line and most effective treatment. However, its efficacy is often challenged by low adherence rates and its effects on comorbid conditions have been questioned. Untreated OSA is associated with multiple health conditions, including hypertension, heart disease, metabolic diseases, cancer, neurodegenerative disorders, depression, and musculoskeletal disorders. The clinical community has reinforced the need for biomarkers for OSA diagnosis, patient stratification, and treatment response monitoring; however, to date, no biomarkers have been validated.

Short (≈ 21-25 nucleotides), single-stranded, non-coding RNAs, known as miRNAs, have been proposed as potential biomarkers in the context of several diseases. The main role of miRNAs is to regulate gene expression post-transcription. These ncRNAs interact with messenger RNAs (mRNAs) through complementary base pairing and promote translational repression or degradation, thereby influencing mRNAs translation and stability. Thus, miRNAs coordinate the expression of multiple genes and act as key regulators of multiple cellular and physiological processes in both health and disease. Several studies have been conducted to identify the miRNA signatures associated with OSA. The identification of dysregulated miRNAs and gene targets may provide relevant insights into the pathophysiology of OSA and its pleiotropic effects, with applications in the clinical management of this disease.

1.2 Key Points

In this context, we proposed mining the existing biomedical literature on dysregulated miRNAs in OSA to construct a unified and structured OSA miRNA database: the OSA miR database. Each entry in the database provides information on 13 items.

  1. Name of the assessed miRNAs

  2. Accession number

  3. Observed change (up-or downregulated) or no change

  4. Biological samples in which miRNA expression was evaluated

  5. Collection time for biological samples

  6. Cohort size

  7. Study groups

  8. Age of the study participants

  9. Body mass index (BMI) of study participants

  10. Apnea-Hypopnea Index (AHI) of the study participants

  11. Comorbidities of the study participants

  12. Correlations between the expression of the studied miRNAs and clinical measurements

  13. Study reference

The compiled data on the OSA miR database constitute a valuable resource for catalyzing future research on OSA molecular mechanisms and identifying biomarkers for clinical application.

3 Methodology

The study protocol that guided this database was registered at the International Prospective Register of Systematic Reviews database (PROSPERO, https://www.crd.york.ac.uk/prospero/), with the title Differential Expression Of MicroRNAs In Obstructive Sleep Apnea: A Systematic Review And Pathway Analysis, on January 1st 2023 (ID: CRD42023386720). A manuscript with the methods originating from this database is currently under submission.

3.1 Eligibility Criteria

For inclusion, studies must have

  1. Assessed individuals with OSA (Apnea and Hypoxia Index [AHI) ≥ 5) and without OSA (AHI < 5), diagnosed based on a full-night sleep study, the gold standard for OSA diagnosis, according to the American Academy of Sleep Medicine (AASM) guidelines

  2. Differentially Expressed (DE) miRNAs, validated by real-time PCR. Some studies were excluded for the following reasons:

  • Lack of patients with and without OSA (control group)

  • Absence of a full-night sleep study for OSA screening, according to the AASM guidelines

  • No validation of DE miRNAs using real-time PCR

  • Included comorbidities in participants’ inclusion criteria (e.g., hypertensive subjects with and without OSA)

  • Presence of inconsistencies in results description

  • Absence of the full-article online

  • Reviews, meta-analyses, case reports, editorials, short-commentaries, or conference proceedings

  • Written in languages other than English, Portuguese, Spanish, or French.  

3.2 Search Strategy and Consulted Databases

The electronic search was conducted on June 20, 2022, without initial date restrictions, using the PubMed/Medline and Web of Science databases. We searched for terms related to OSA and miRNAs [(OSA OR Sleep Apnea or Sleep Apnoea OR Obstructive Sleep Apnea OR Obstructive Sleep Apnoea) AND (miRNAs OR miRs OR microRNAs OR small RNAs)], without language restrictions. Duplicates from the different databases were removed.

3.3 Study Selection Process

The identified studies were screened according to the defined inclusion and exclusion criteria based on the study title (Phase I) and abstract (Phase II). Full manuscripts of the selected studies were retrieved and assessed for eligibility (Phase III). Two independent reviewers performed all the phases of the study selection process. Any disagreement between the two independent reviewers at any of the study phases was resolved by discussion with a third reviewer if needed.

3.4 Data Collection and Analysis

Each study was summarized in terms of the study design, demographic, and clinical characteristics of the enrolled participants, and obtained results. We retrieved Differentially Expressed miRNAs reported in patients with OSA relative to control subjects from eligible studies. miRNAs were grouped based on the accession numbers obtained from miRBase. The data collection was performed by a single author. A second author cross-checked all the data and confirmed its accuracy. Any disagreement was resolved through discussion and the involvement of a third author. The obtained results were used to build an online database of OSA miRs on the GitHub platform.

3.5 Inclusion of New Studies

The inclusion of future studies and updates of the OSA miR database will be performed following the same eligibility criteria. The literature search will be updated annually. Studies can also be submitted in this form. All submissions will be analyzed for inclusion in the database following the same criteria.


Do you want to add your study to the OSA miRNA database?
Please contact us at sleepapneaid.cnc-at-gmail.com (replace -at- with @). We will analyze the study and update the database if the study is eligible.
